        <name>6.2.2.1 Hyperbolic Identities</name>
        <questiontext>&lt;h3&gt;Hyperbolic Identities&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;p&gt;The hyperbolic functions &lt;span class="math inline"&gt;\(\cosh x\) and \(\sinh x\)&lt;/span&gt; satisfy similar (but not exactly equivalent) identities to those satisfied by &lt;span class="math inline"&gt;\(\cos x\) and \(\sin x\)&lt;/span&gt;. We note first some basic notation similar to that employed with trigonometric functions: &lt;span class="math inline"&gt;\(\cosh^nx\)&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;means&amp;nbsp;&lt;span class="math inline"&gt;\((\cosh x)^n\), \(\sinh^nx\)&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;means&amp;nbsp;&lt;span class="math inline"&gt;\((\sinh x)^n\) for \(n\ne -1\).&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;span class="math inline"&gt;In&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;the special case that &lt;span class="math inline"&gt;\(n=-1\)&lt;/span&gt; we &lt;span&gt;&lt;strong&gt;do not&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt; use &lt;span class="math inline"&gt;\(\cosh^{-1}x\)&lt;/span&gt; and &lt;span class="math inline"&gt;\(\sinh^{-1}x\)&lt;/span&gt; to mean the reciprocals of the expressions. The notation &lt;span class="math inline"&gt;\(\cosh^{-1}x\)&lt;/span&gt; and &lt;span class="math inline"&gt;\(\sinh^{-1}x\)&lt;/span&gt; is reserved for the &lt;span&gt;&lt;strong&gt;inverse functions&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt; of &lt;span class="math inline"&gt;\(\cosh x\)&lt;/span&gt; and &lt;span class="math inline"&gt;\(\sinh x\)&lt;/span&gt; respectively.&lt;/p&gt;</questiontext>
